{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9f1dd179-008b-4b98-a95f-eafb9cb1f1a2","content":"The standard approach is to **wrap file system calls behind an interface** and inject it:\n\n```csharp\npublic interface IFileSystem\n{\n    string ReadAllText(string path);\n    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n    bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n}\n```\n\nThen a real implementation delegates to `System.IO`:\n\n```csharp\npublic class FileSystem : IFileSystem\n{\n    public string ReadAllText(string path) => File.ReadAllText(path);\n    public void WriteAllText(string path, string contents) => File.WriteAllText(path, contents);\n    public bool DirectoryExists(string path) => Directory.Exists(path);\n}\n```\n\nIn tests, you mock/fake `IFileSystem` instead of touching disk.\n\n**Alternatively**, the [`System.IO.Abstractions`](https://www.nuget.org/packages/System.IO.Abstractions) NuGet package provides a ready-made `IFileSystem` interface (with an in-memory test helper) so you don't have to maintain your own wrapper.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9cbafd46-81a4-46d0-b591-223e2f020170","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to make file system operations (`File.WriteAllText`, `File.ReadAllText`, `Directory.Exists`) testable in their .NET project. This is a design/architecture question, not a code change request.\n\nThe standard approach is to abstract file system operations behind an interface, then use dependency injection to provide either the real implementation or a mock/fake in tests.\n\nLet me give a concise answer.","outputTokens":365,"requestId":"BC5D:2EF3EB:2069C19:23D0F3E:69FA9C11"},"id":"143781b4-8190-4421-a005-ee9c6673ea91","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:40:42.044Z","parentId":"f43e3be7-4b4d-43c5-8df2-22b969c84785"}
